So I think every larger company will probably have their own sort of, you know, layers of

00:38:11.439 --> 00:38:16.560
control, right? So there is privacy partners on one side, like they tell you, you know,

00:38:17.439 --> 00:38:21.919
this is the data I want to use. This is what you're allowed to do with the data. And being able

00:38:21.919 --> 00:38:26.719
to have those conversations, that's important. And then you have sort of like the frameworks that

00:38:26.719 --> 00:38:31.040
are sort of like set by whoever is their sort of like security team, right? So we call them

00:38:31.040 --> 00:38:36.959
enterprise protect. And typically, it's important to understand sort of the guardrails that they've

00:38:36.959 --> 00:38:42.239
put in place. So in our case, you know, the way that it works is that, okay, well, you have this

00:38:42.239 --> 00:38:47.679
zone. In this zone, you're allowed to do X, Y, Z. And this is sort of like the guardrails that

00:38:47.679 --> 00:38:52.399
are put in place. And then if there are existing patterns that, you know, the architecture team

00:38:52.399 --> 00:38:57.439
has kind of put in place, as long as you stay within those, you're kind of okay. Now, the

00:38:57.520 --> 00:39:03.919
difficulty happens if you have like a use case that doesn't really fit those patterns. And that's

00:39:03.919 --> 00:39:08.320
where it becomes challenging. So, you know, I can kind of speak to that, because we had those

00:39:08.320 --> 00:39:13.919
challenges. Because when we were migrating our Posit Connect platform onto Azure, they were like,

00:39:13.919 --> 00:39:20.719
well, the Azure environment isn't really made to have data coming into it in this kind of fashion,

00:39:20.719 --> 00:39:26.879
right? So that, again, was not an easy conversation, because they had to understand exactly what is

00:39:26.879 --> 00:39:31.360
going on, they had to build new patterns. But once we got to the point that, you know, the patterns

00:39:31.360 --> 00:39:36.159
were built, all the conversations were had, Enterprise Protect gave their sign off, now you

00:39:36.159 --> 00:39:41.120
have this pattern that you have that you can reuse and kind of do whatever use case that you need to,

00:39:41.120 --> 00:39:48.639
right? So I think the key here is to be able to like abstract your use case into a pattern that

00:39:48.639 --> 00:39:54.000
you can kind of explain to the partners and say, like, this is what I need to do. And you also have

00:39:54.000 --> 00:39:59.520
to be kind of like, you know, open at the end of the day that they say, like, okay, well, you know,

00:39:59.520 --> 00:40:03.760
to make your data secure, you need to do X, Y, Z, and kind of like hear them out as well. So

00:40:04.879 --> 00:40:09.760
that it's not it's not easy. And especially if I take the consultant point of view, I feel like

00:40:09.760 --> 00:40:15.199
that's particularly difficult, because you know, you you're kind of like time bound. And some of

00:40:15.199 --> 00:40:19.360
these things, I'll be honest, we just take a lot of time and a lot of, you know, effort to kind of

00:40:19.360 --> 00:40:23.760
like, get things going. With that said, the benefit that you have on the consultant side,

00:40:23.760 --> 00:40:28.879
I think is that, you know, if you're paid by the company, they want to see results. So I would say

00:40:28.879 --> 00:40:34.479
use your business partners to kind of like, you know, push some of those conversations along with

00:40:34.479 --> 00:40:38.239
the security partners and say, like, you know, so they understand the value, because a lot of

00:40:38.239 --> 00:40:44.239
the conversations that we've had, you know, I can see is like, if I go to them with like a use case,

00:40:44.239 --> 00:40:48.159
and I say, hey, I need to do this, and it requires some new patterns, they're gonna be like, no,

00:40:48.159 --> 00:40:53.120
we're not going to do this. And essentially, if I look at it from their perspective, like,

00:40:53.120 --> 00:41:00.239
why am I going to bother creating some potential risk for this thing that you're coming to me,

00:41:00.239 --> 00:41:03.760
right? So you do need to have that support from the business side that says, like, no,

00:41:03.760 --> 00:41:09.600
this is important. This is going to enable lots of value for us. And we need your help to tell us

00:41:09.600 --> 00:41:15.120
like how to do this, but do it within whatever like risk appetite that you have. Once you have

00:41:15.120 --> 00:41:19.600
that support, it becomes a lot easier to kind of push things along. But you do need to have your

00:41:19.600 --> 00:41:23.679
business partners there that who are, you know, paying you to say, like, hey, I need you guys

00:41:23.679 --> 00:41:28.479
to support this, because whatever you're paying me for, I can't do if you know, they don't they

00:41:28.479 --> 00:41:38.239
don't help me out. Thank you for such a thoughtful answer. Gerard, I see you have your hand raised.

